Mr Said Swaleh, a conductor with one of the Lamu-bound buses, called on security agencies in the region to come up with strategies that will ensure the safety of passengers while at the same time ensuring there are no delays.
"For the past 10 months, we've been enjoying the travel arrangements on the Lamu-Witu-Garsen road. There have been no delays. We're worried that due to yesterday’s attack, more restrictions will be introduced that will cause delays. I hope that won't be the case," said Mr Swaleh.
Patrols intensified
A spot-check by the Nation established that general security patrols on the Lamu-Witu-Garsen road had also been intensified as police and Kenya Defence Forces (KDF) vehicles kept moving along the various sections of the route, particularly those that are considered to be terror hotspots such as Nyongoro, Lango la Simba, Milihoi and Mambo Sasa.



