Mercy Kahindi, a passenger aboard a shuttle heading to Mombasa from Lamu, said they were forced to wait and move in one convoy escorted by armed police officers.
"Shuttles have always been moving without waiting for the convoy of buses. Today, we were asked to wait for buses so that we can move in one convoy under police escort. This is unusual," said Ms Kahindi.
Locals interviewed by the Nation expressed disappointment, saying that the Sunday attempted Al-Shabaab attack at Nyongoro has broken the trust they had over the security of travellers on the road.
"Over 10 months have passed without witnessing any Al-Shabaab incident on our route. This had brought much confidence among travellers that terrorist attacks in Lamu were fading. The Sunday attack came as a shock to us," said Mr Omar Ali.
Travel by air
Other frequent road users said they will have to consider travelling by air rather than using the road and risk getting killed by the militants.
"I now find it hard to believe that we're safe to continue travelling by road. There are security agencies patrolling every place along the road but, unfortunately, Al-Shabaab are still launching attacks. That means the security situation on the Lamu-Garsen route is still questionable. I can't use the road any more. I prefer using air transport since you're guaranteed of your security," said Ms Milcah Kimani.



