Contacted, Lamu County Commissioner Irungu Macharia said the county’s security committee will convene an urgent meeting to strategise on travel arrangements on the Lamu-Witu-Garsen route during this festive season.
"Following yesterday’s incident, we're meeting as security stakeholders to find an effective approach that will ensure safety of the commuters plying the Lamu-Witu-Garsen-Mombasa route. I will give details later," said Mr Macharia on Monday.
Shabaab attacks
Between 2014 and 2017, the Lamu-Garsen route witnessed frequent ambushes and attacks by Al-Shabaab militants on security and public transport vehicles plying the road.
A number of security personnel and civilians lost their lives on the route.
The national government was forced to introduce a night travel ban on the route on July 19, 2014 after seven people, including four Administration Police officers, were killed by Al-Shabaab terrorists who ambushed a Tahmeed bus en route to Lamu from Mombasa near Mambo Sasa forest in Witu.
Public service vehicles were instead directed to move in one convoy that is normally accompanied by an armed police escort.
The government also moved in to establish General Service Unit (GSU) and KDF camps at all notorious hotspots along the route.



